For Alabama's students, the months away from school can result in a large loss of knowledge in reading, math, science and other core subject matter. The Alabama Summer Learning Challenge raises awareness of the summer loss epidemic, shares research on the importance of personalized activities and provides access to a variety of free resources to targeted summer learning. Click on this link to access summer learning resources...

post_text: This is a reminder that anytime your income changes you may apply for the meals benefit program. This includes COVID-19. If your family's income has been affected you may apply for free/reduced meals for when school returns. The eligibility will be good for 30 days into the 2020-2021 School Year. If the application is approved you will have to re-apply before September 21, 2020 to continue to receive the benefit for the 2020-2021 School Year. To apply online for Free or Reduced School Breakfast and Lunch please go to https://paypams.com/OnlineApp.aspx. We will be processing applications while school is not in session.

post_text:
Parents, the flu is still going strong. We ask that if your child has a fever that you do not send him/her back to school until they are without fever for at least 24 hours. To lessen the spread of germs, please review with your child to cover their mouth with their elbow when they cough, to keep their hands off of their face/mouth, and to wash their hands when possible.

We want to keep all of our students healthy and we ask that you help us with these tips at home.

By April 1, 2020, households will receive an invitation to participate in the 2020 census. There are 3 options for responding: online, by mail, or by phone.

Why is this important? The federal government uses census numbers to allocate more than $675 billion in federal funds annually for community programs such as education programs, housing development, and health care services for the elderly. Please be sure to fill out the 2020 census!

post_text: From Superintendent Ann West: It is an honor to be a part of Marion County Schools! Our State Report Cards were released this morning and our district increased from an 87 to 88. Congratulations to each of our schools!
